metadata.name: DOM II #174
metadata.description:
Owners of DOM will receive FREE AirDrop!

From Proto-Indo-European *dṓm (“house, home”), from root *dem- (“to build”).

The humans use of stone in architecture and housing dates back to the dawn of civilisation, where its excellence in material, ecological and aesthetic qualities recalls the original concept of home, intended as a shelter from the external world.
The word Home is more representing of the true meaning of DOM as it is tied to the sense of family, homeland and provenance. The place where the heart is.

As a culmination of my personal generative art journey, the DOM II is a natural sequel and a closer, much deeper & intimate look to ancient cities/ villages architecture and typical stone houses. Inspired by Dalmatia coastal & Herzegovina hinterland but you will hopefully find your own dream home.

Thank You!


Press 's' to save the canvas or ‘2’ (or ‘H’) for a HD image resolution PNG.
For printing super hires press '4' (can be slow).

Vanilla 2D p5js without additional libraries.
Created with love for code and generative art. 

@Qotonana
December, 2024.

metadata.name: Chromatographies #242
metadata.description:
Chromatographie (chromatography) is a word that comes from the Greek χρῶμα (khroma): meaning “color” and γράφειν (graphein): meaning “to write”.

This work is an abstract study of colors their mixture or separation as well as their place in space or their absence.

I've had a lot of fun (and time!) trying to make a realistic digital rendering that could pass for a physical work and I hope you'll enjoy it as much as I did.

2024 dec
---
type s to save to png
Code written in javascript/webgl2
Please note that the GPU is very busy during rendering.
Tested on chrome/brave

metadata.name: Scaffold #231
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #118
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Obliques #175
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Warped #18
metadata.description:
A free little toy.  Play with it and it might make art!  This is my second project using a shader.  It starts by making a simple drawing, then the shader uses noise to warp the image.  I'm making it free because 1) You really have to work at it to make art (but I think it's a lot of fun to tinker with!), and 2) the capture sometimes has minor variances from the final image - couldn't figure it out.  Made with p5js and uses some Perlin noise code by Inigo Quilez.  

After opening, press "s" to save a large jpg.

metadata.name: Flux Mesh #1
metadata.description:
This is my take on 3D simplex noise. Time is a dimension here.

Square size and color are determined by noise value over time.

Each NFT iteration has randomized color scheme, grid size, and noise zoom.
